				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} v(\varvec{s},\varvec{w},\theta )= f(y(\varvec{s},\varvec{w}) - \theta ), \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M128" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>v</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">s</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">w</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>&#x003b8;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">s</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">w</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>&#x003b8;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_Equ9.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>where <inline-formula id="IEq57"><alternatives><tex-math id="M129">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\theta \in \mathbb {R}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M130"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>&#x003b8;</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02208;</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq57.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is the &#x0201c;firing&#x0201d; threshold and <inline-formula id="IEq58"><alternatives><tex-math id="M131">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f:\mathbb {R}\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M132"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo>:</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">&#x02192;</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq58.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is the transfer function (Fig.&#x000a0; <xref rid="Fig2" ref-type="fig">2</xref>): <inline-formula id="IEq59"><alternatives><tex-math id="M133">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f \in {\mathcal {C}}(\mathbb {R})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M134"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02208;</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="script">C</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq59.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, <italic>f</italic> is locally Lipschitz, <inline-formula id="IEq60"><alternatives><tex-math id="M135">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f(u)=0$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M136"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>u</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq60.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> for <inline-formula id="IEq61"><alternatives><tex-math id="M137">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$u\in (-\infty ,0]$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M138"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>u</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02208;</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>&#x0221e;</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq61.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, and <inline-formula id="IEq62"><alternatives><tex-math id="M139">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f(u)&#x0003e;0$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M140"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>f</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>u</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>&#x0003e;</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq62.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> for <inline-formula id="IEq63"><alternatives><tex-math id="M141">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$u\in (0,\infty )$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M142"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>u</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02208;</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>&#x0221e;</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq63.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p><p id="Par21">Model (<xref rid="Equ8" ref-type="">8</xref>), (<xref rid="Equ9" ref-type="">9</xref>) captures the summation of postsynaptic potentials and the threshold nature of the neuronal activation but disregards the specific dynamics accounted for in other more advanced models. Nevertheless, as we will show in Sect. <xref rid="Sec7" ref-type="sec">4</xref>, this phenomenological model is already sufficient to explain the fundamental properties of information processing discussed in Sect. <xref rid="Sec2" ref-type="sec">2</xref>.</p></sec><sec id="Sec6"><title>Synaptic Plasticity</title><p id="Par22">In addition to the basic neuronal response mechanism (Sect. <xref rid="Sec5" ref-type="sec">3.2</xref>), we also model the synaptic plasticity. The description adopted here relies on the neuronal firing rate and Hebbian learning. Such a learning rule implies that the dynamics of <inline-formula id="IEq64"><alternatives><tex-math id="M143">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varvec{w}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M144"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">w</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq64.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> should depend on the product of the input signal, <inline-formula id="IEq65"><alternatives><tex-math id="M145">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varvec{s}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M146"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">s</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq65.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, and the neuronal output, <italic>v</italic>. We thus arrive to a modified classical Oja rule (Oja <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR34">1982</xref>):<disp-formula id="Equ10"><label>10</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M147">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
