				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varvec{s}_i \in {\mathcal {S}}({\mathcal {M}})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M454"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">s</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>&#x02208;</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="script">S</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="script">M</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq205.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>?</p><p id="Par49">Below we will show that this is indeed possible, provided that the neuronal dimensionality, <italic>n</italic>, is large enough. Moreover, the separation can be achieved by a neuron with the vector of synaptic weights, <inline-formula id="IEq206"><alternatives><tex-math id="M455">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
