				\begin{document}$$n\in [1,10]$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M714"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mo>&#x02208;</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">[</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mn>10</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">]</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="11538_2018_415_Article_IEq319.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>), neuronal selectivity to a single stimulus does not form. It emerges rapidly when the dimension parameter <italic>n</italic> exceeds some critical value, around <inline-formula id="IEq320"><alternatives><tex-math id="M715">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
